<div id="review_3298635801" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3298635801" />
    <a title="Indrė" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/75674282-indr"><img alt="Indrė" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1514542063p2/75674282.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3298635801?book_show_action=true">Jun 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Indrė" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Indrė" href="/user/show/75674282-indr">Indrė</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9786090139004" href="/book/show/51321564-dangaus-atradimas">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3298635801" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer205057766078474327">This was a hard book to begin with. The whole appeal for me was, that it was structured around two angels on a mission on earth. Sounds easy enough. Expect, it was everything but. The book was about everything. And I do mean about everything. <br/>At first, I was confused - if there&apos;s this huge mission ahead, why do I read about these insignificant little meaningless things? Why is this so detailed and where does this go? But then I realized that the book was like a puzzle - everything, even the tini</span>
  <span id="freeText205057766078474327" style="display:none">This was a hard book to begin with. The whole appeal for me was, that it was structured around two angels on a mission on earth. Sounds easy enough. Expect, it was everything but. The book was about everything. And I do mean about everything. <br />At first, I was confused - if there's this huge mission ahead, why do I read about these insignificant little meaningless things? Why is this so detailed and where does this go? But then I realized that the book was like a puzzle - everything, even the tiniest little insignificant detail was a important piece in the whole big picture. And wow, when it all started to make sense - what a joy this book became. <br />The book covers religion, art, history, science, astrology, love-triangles, holocaust, politics, music... everything. Curve-ball after a curve-ball, and yeah, don't get too attached to main characters, cuz it's Game Of Thrones all over again... <br />I don't even know if I would recommend this book to anyone. Yes, I think this is an important read, and everyone should read it, but I don't think everyone can read it. It's probably a hidden masterpiece not everyone will get a pleasure to enjoy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="205057766078474327" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


