    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_414952332" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/414952332" />
    <a title="Antithesis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12853654-antithesis"><img alt="Antithesis" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/414952332?book_show_action=true">Sep 15, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Antithesis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Antithesis" href="/user/show/12853654-antithesis">Antithesis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer414952332" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5762114323714969289">This book is the size of a word book, but your time is better spent just reading definitions from a word book. It starts off promising, but it soon becomes apparent that the plot has no direction whatsoever, and that it&apos;s just a container for a couple of pseudo-scientific/philosophic passages. Those passages weren&apos;t necessarily bad, but most of them were of the level of &quot;tell me something new.&quot; They are in no way good enough to justify the book, especially considering the fact that those passage</span>
  <span id="freeText5762114323714969289" style="display:none">This book is the size of a word book, but your time is better spent just reading definitions from a word book. It starts off promising, but it soon becomes apparent that the plot has no direction whatsoever, and that it's just a container for a couple of pseudo-scientific/philosophic passages. Those passages weren't necessarily bad, but most of them were of the level of "tell me something new." They are in no way good enough to justify the book, especially considering the fact that those passages is really the only thing the book is building up to.<br /><br />And the plot doesn't even do a good job of covering up the fact that the author just wanted do literary masturbating. With that plot, those passages fall completely out of place. It's clear that the author's formula was "write a seemingly normal plot, but once every 50 pages, I get deep and surrealistic." It feels forced and pretentious. I'll give a more concrete idea of what those supposedly interesting passages are. The author split himself up into the three main characters for this book (that's not even an accusation; he does that more often and gives hints of this by describing the characters's appearances as that of himself). Those passages are dialogs between any of those characters. Kind of like an interview the author was having with himself.<br /><br />In all honesty, I think the book would be better if it was abridged to just those passages. The now-dead author gets his way of sharing what he wanted to share, the reader gets his way of not having to read through 900 pages of uninteresting plot for no reason, and it saves trees. I've read many books by Mulisch, and I can tell you that he was not being Mulisch. The only thing I can imagine he was thinking, is that his books had too high a concentration of surrealism which greater audiences might dislike, so he made a lame excuse for a plot that's filled with clichés. It's kind of a Mulisch-lite, to introduce people to his style (although that doesn't explain why the book had to be 900 pages, then. That remains a mystery.)<br /><br />Another key thing about him that's missing in this book, is coherence. His books are usually filled with it, so much so that the prologue of The Diamond jokingly announces something along the lines of "this will be the start of a story with strange coherences that only become clear afterwards!" And that's true, for most of his work. But here, the reader is left with nothing, at the end, but a very rushed epilogue that again raises the longing of being told something new for a change. But there isn't anything new except the feeling of betrayal.<br /><br />My last complaint: the author makes up an interesting but unscientific invention in this book. He proposes the idea that, theoretically speaking, one can see the past by looking at the stars. The light that the earth reflected from the sun 1000 years ago, would have hit a star 500 light-years away, get reflected, and return to the earth again by now. Despite the fact that only a very small portion of the light reflected from the star, shows the events on earth 1000 years ago, it should be possible to take only the light you want, amplify it, and get a clear look at the past.<br /><br />This is completely false. I'm in my first year of engineering physics, and one of the first things I learnt is that stars are black bodies: they absorb all the light they receive. The light you see when looking at the sun, is entirely the result of nuclear fusion. There's no reflection. And yet Mulisch has an astronomer confirm that this theory (which a child thought of) is possible, and it's a recurring concept in the book. Mulisch loved the natural science and it's possible that he simply was not aware of this, but that's no excuse. Compare it to what he did for The Procedure, which deals a lot with chemistry: he went to actual chemists for lectures, made notes, asked all the questions he needed to ask, and then used the material for his book.<br /><br />In an interview a couple months before his death [1], when asked if he sees popularity as a good way of determining how good a book is, Mulisch answered: "by that logic, Kluun (a Dutch writer who's very popular but is also very much criticized; replace with Stephenie Meyer if you aren't Dutch) is the best writer of them all. I don't think so." Take the author's own advice and don't read this book. If you want to read Mulisch, read The Procedure.<br /><br />Sources:<br />1. <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.novatv.nl/page/detail/uitzendingen/7567/NOVA%20College%20Tour%20met%20Harry%20Mulisch">http://www.novatv.nl/page/detail/uitz...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="5762114323714969289" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


